#### 5c. `list_my_guides` Tool (`src/lib/mcp/tools/list-my-guides.ts`)

```typescript
// src/lib/mcp/tools/list-my-guides.ts
import { McpServer } from "@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/mcp.js";
import { z } from "zod";
import { createClient } from "@supabase/supabase-js";
import { slugify } from "@/lib/utils";

export function registerListMyGuidesTool(server: McpServer, userId: string) {
  server.registerTool(
    "list_my_guides",
    {
      title: "List My Guides",
      description: "List your existing guides on Pathway, including drafts.",
      inputSchema: z.object({
        include_hidden: z.boolean().optional().default(true)
          .describe("Include hidden/draft guides. Defaults to true."),
        limit: z.number().optional().default(20)
          .describe("Max number of guides to return. Defaults to 20."),
      }),
    },
    async ({ include_hidden, limit }) => {
      const supabase = createClient(
        process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL!,
        process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY!
      );

      let query = supabase
        .from("posts")
        .select("id, title, description, is_hidden, created_at, likes_count, difficulty, guide_type, techs")
        .eq("user_id", userId)
        .order("created_at", { ascending: false })
        .limit(limit);

      if (!include_hidden) {
        query = query.eq("is_hidden", false);
      }

      const { data: guides, error } = await query;

      if (error) {
        return {
          content: [{ type: "text", text: `Error fetching guides: ${error.message}` }],
          isError: true,
        };
      }

      if (!guides || guides.length === 0) {
        return {
          content: [{ type: "text", text: "You have no guides yet." }],
        };
      }

      const baseUrl = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL || "https://pathway.app";
      const formatted = guides.map((g) => {
        const status = g.is_hidden ? "[DRAFT]" : "[PUBLISHED]";
        const url = `${baseUrl}/guide/${g.id}/${slugify(g.title)}`;
        return `${status} ${g.title}\n  ${g.description?.slice(0, 100)}${(g.description?.length ?? 0) > 100 ? "..." : ""}\n  Likes: ${g.likes_count} | Type: ${g.guide_type} | Techs: ${g.techs.join(", ") || "none"}\n  URL: ${url}`;
      }).join("\n\n");

      return {
        content: [{ type: "text", text: `Your guides (${guides.length}):\n\n${formatted}` }],
      };
    }
  );
}
```

### 6. Creating a Guide Without Steps (Blocks + Chat Messages Only)

Looking at the existing code, the `publishGuide` function in `src/lib/supabase/queries/create-guide.ts` (lines 111-177) handles steps and step_blocks as optional -- it only inserts them if `state.steps.length > 0`. The guide detail page similarly handles the case where there are no steps.

For MCP-created guides, the approach is:
- Insert the `posts` row with all metadata.
- Insert `guide_blocks` from the parsed JSONL (with auto-categorization).
- Insert `chat_messages` for backward compatibility with the timeline view.
- Skip `guide_steps` and `step_blocks` entirely -- they remain empty.

The guide detail page already renders the chat timeline view when no steps exist (it falls back to showing `chat_messages` via the `ChatTimeline` component at `src/components/timeline/chat-timeline.tsx`). This means MCP-created guides will display correctly as a raw conversation timeline, which is a perfectly valid viewing experience.

Users can later visit the guide's edit page in the web UI to organize the blocks into steps if they want a more structured presentation.

The `is_hidden` flag is used for draft mode:
- `publish: false` (default) sets `is_hidden: true` -- the guide is not visible in public listings but the creator can see it on their profile.
- `publish: true` sets `is_hidden: false` -- immediately visible to everyone.

### 7. Configuration Instructions for Users

After deploying, users add this to their Claude Code MCP configuration file (`~/.claude/settings.json` or project-level `.mcp.json`):

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "pathway": {
      "type": "streamable-http",
      "url": "https://your-pathway-app.com/api/mcp",
      "oauth": {
        "authorizationUrl": "https://<project-ref>.supabase.co/auth/v1/oauth/authorize",
        "tokenUrl": "https://<project-ref>.supabase.co/auth/v1/oauth/token",
        "clientId": "<your-oauth-client-id>",
        "scopes": ["openid", "email"]
      }
    }
  }
}
```

**Alternative**: If Claude Code supports MCP's built-in OAuth discovery via the `.well-known` endpoint, the user may only need:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "pathway": {
      "type": "streamable-http",
      "url": "https://your-pathway-app.com/api/mcp"
    }
  }
}
```

The MCP client would then discover the OAuth configuration by fetching `https://your-pathway-app.com/.well-known/oauth-authorization-server` (which we may need to proxy/serve) or the Supabase discovery endpoint directly.

**Note on discovery endpoint**: For the MCP client to auto-discover OAuth, we may need to serve a `.well-known/oauth-authorization-server` document from the Pathway app itself. This can be done with a simple route:

```typescript
// src/app/.well-known/oauth-authorization-server/route.ts
import { NextResponse } from "next/server";

export async function GET() {
  const supabaseUrl = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL!;
  return NextResponse.json({
    issuer: supabaseUrl,
    authorization_endpoint: `${supabaseUrl}/auth/v1/oauth/authorize`,
    token_endpoint: `${supabaseUrl}/auth/v1/oauth/token`,
    jwks_uri: `${supabaseUrl}/auth/v1/.well-known/jwks.json`,
    response_types_supported: ["code"],
    grant_types_supported: ["authorization_code", "refresh_token"],
    code_challenge_methods_supported: ["S256"],
  });
}
```

### 8. Middleware Update

The existing middleware at `src/middleware.ts` matches all routes except static files. This is fine -- the MCP route at `/api/mcp` will be matched, and the middleware calls `supabase.auth.getUser()` to refresh the session. For MCP requests, there is no cookie-based session, so the middleware will harmlessly find no session. However, we should ensure the middleware does not interfere with or reject MCP requests.

The current middleware (in `src/lib/supabase/middleware.ts`) simply attempts to refresh the session and returns `NextResponse.next()` regardless of whether a session exists. This is safe for MCP requests -- it will simply pass through.

No changes to the middleware are needed.

